    var COMPREHENSIVE_FAQ_FINAL = [
      { q: 'What is the smallest scale aquaculture operation I can start?', a: 'A 4-acre Limited Purpose Aquaculture (LPA) lease with $25-50K capital can be a viable starting point. Many successful Maine farms began this way. You\'ll need: lease application, basic gear (cages or bags), used workboat or skiff, dock access, seed supply, and customer relationships. Plan to be cash-flow negative for 18-30 months before first harvest.' },
      { q: 'How long does it take to get a Maine aquaculture lease?', a: 'LPA leases: 3-6 months. Standard leases: 6-24 months. Federal coordination (ESA, ACOE, EPA) can add months. Plan 12-24 months from idea to operations as realistic minimum.' },
      { q: 'What are the biggest mistakes new aquaculture farmers make?', a: '(1) Skipping community engagement; (2) underestimating capital + cash flow needs; (3) overstocking before learning site; (4) treating it as part-time when it requires sustained attention; (5) ignoring records discipline; (6) buying gear before having buyers; (7) not investing in safety culture.' },
      { q: 'Can I make a living from a single-acre oyster farm?', a: 'Probably not as sole income. A 4-acre LPA farm at typical productivity can generate $15-30K/year — supplemental income or lifestyle business. Full-time living wage requires 15-25+ acres or vertical integration.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the most profitable Maine aquaculture species right now?', a: 'Per acre: oyster + kelp lead margins for small operations. Per labor hour: kelp + mussel scale well. Bangs Island scale mussel + IMTA is most profitable model. Salmon at industrial scale is highest revenue but requires major capital.' },
      { q: 'How do I find a mentor in Maine aquaculture?', a: 'Maine Aquaculture Association (MAA) coordinates apprenticeships + mentoring. CEI provides technical assistance with loans. Hurricane Island + GMRI run training programs. Reach out to farms; many welcome interested apprentices.' },
      { q: 'Where do I get high-quality oyster seed?', a: 'Mook Sea Farm (Walpole) is largest Maine seed supplier. Maine Fresh Sea Farms (Walpole) + Pacific Oyster Co. Bagaduce Hatchery (Brooklin). Order in February-March for May deployment.' },
      { q: 'How much can I expect to earn from a 25-acre commercial oyster farm?', a: 'Mature operation can generate $200-400K/year revenue with $60-120K profit. Requires 2-3 staff + 24-30 months from seed to harvest. Profitability depends on growing conditions, mortality rates, market access, and brand premium.' },
      { q: 'Should I focus on one species or diversify?', a: 'Diversification reduces risk + smooths cash flow. Oyster + kelp + mussel combination (Bangs Island IMTA model) is increasingly common. Single-species focus allows specialization + brand building. New farmers should consider starting with one species, expanding after 3-5 years.' },
      { q: 'How does climate change affect my farm planning?', a: 'Gulf of Maine warming 5x faster than global average. Effects: species range shifts, heat stress, ocean acidification, storms. Plan adaptation: site selection cooler/deeper, species mix, gear engineering for storms, hatchery buffer systems. Climate-resilient species (kelp, bivalves) gain market advantage.' },
      { q: 'What insurance do I need?', a: 'Minimum: stock insurance, gear insurance, vessel insurance, workers comp, general liability. Recommended: pollution liability, product liability, business interruption. Cost: 2-5% of revenue annually. CEI + specialized aquaculture insurers serve Maine market.' },
      { q: 'How do I handle a biotoxin closure?', a: 'NSSP closure forces shellfish hold or destruction during closure period. Plan ahead: have crop insurance covering biotoxin events. Communication with buyers about closure status. Hold + grow during short closures (1-4 weeks). Sell quickly after re-opening to clear inventory.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the lifespan of a typical oyster farm?', a: 'Standard DMR lease is 10 years renewable. Many farms operate 20-40+ years with renewals. Gear has cycles: cages 8-12 years, longlines 5-10 years, anchors 10-20 years, mussel rafts 15-25 years. Plan capital replacements throughout.' },
      { q: 'How do I balance aquaculture work with family life?', a: 'Aquaculture is demanding, especially during peak seasons. Plan staffing redundancy. Establish quality off-duty time. Bring family to dock + farm so they understand work. Many successful farms are family businesses where work + family are integrated.' },
      { q: 'What if my community opposes my project?', a: 'Listen + engage early. Adjust project to address concerns. Withdraw if necessary; not every site is appropriate. American Aquafarms 2022 demonstrated that community opposition can defeat legally permitted projects. Build relationships through community presence + hiring + transparency.' },
      { q: 'Can I be both fisherman + aquaculturalist?', a: 'Yes — many lobstermen are now also kelp farmers (winter season). Atlantic Sea Farms contracts with ~27 lobstermen specifically for kelp. The skills + gear overlap well. Plan time + capital for both.' },
      { q: 'How do I deal with bad weather + storm damage?', a: 'Insurance is critical. Pre-storm gear stow + reinforcement protocols. Submerged + storm-rated gear. Industry mutual aid for recovery. Climate change is making severe weather more frequent.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the role of indigenous communities in Maine aquaculture?', a: 'Wabanaki nations (Passamaquoddy, Penobscot, Mi\'kmaq, Maliseet, Abenaki) have aboriginal + treaty rights to fishery + shellfish access. Tribal-owned aquaculture programs growing. New projects should include government-to-government tribal consultation. Indigenous knowledge integrating into research + management.' },
      { q: 'How do I become certified organic or ASC?', a: 'Apply through third-party certifier. Annual audits + ongoing compliance. Cost $10-30K per facility + annual fees. Higher premium pricing typically offsets costs. ASC + BAP most common for salmon; organic limited US options.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the difference between farm-gate value and retail value?', a: 'Farm-gate = price farmer receives. Retail = consumer pays. Distributor + restaurant typically take 30-50% markup. $1 oyster at farm = $3+ at restaurant. Distribution channel choice affects margin significantly.' },
      { q: 'How important is brand-building for Maine aquaculture?', a: 'Critical. Pemaquid + Glidden Point + Bangs Island brands earn premium pricing across decades. Brand investment is essential but takes 5-10+ years to mature. Quality consistency + story-telling + customer relationships build brand together.' },
      { q: 'What new species or technologies should I watch?', a: 'Scallop ear-hanging (UMaine + Hurricane Island research); land-based RAS (Whole Oceans, Kingfish); microalgae for biofuel + feed; lumpfish for sea lice control; new kelp species; offshore wind co-location; carbon credit verification methodology.' },
      { q: 'How do I get from idea to operational farm in 5 years?', a: 'Year 1-2: education + research + business planning. Year 2-3: permit + financing. Year 3-4: deploy + initial harvest. Year 4-5: optimize + grow. Realistic timeline. Shortcuts often lead to failure or community opposition.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the future of Maine aquaculture in 2030 + 2040?', a: 'Conservative estimate: $300M industry by 2030; $500M+ by 2040. Diversification of species + models; climate adaptation widespread; equity + indigenous participation expanded; carbon credit revenue contributing; Maine model exported globally.' },
      { q: 'How does aquaculture compare to traditional fishing?', a: 'Aquaculture: consistent supply, controllable quality, year-round production, lower environmental footprint per unit production. Fishing: traditional + cultural value, less capital intensive entry, dependence on wild populations. Both can coexist + complement each other.' },
      { q: 'What is IMTA and why does it matter?', a: 'IMTA = Integrated Multi-Trophic Aquaculture. Combine species from different food-web levels (fish + shellfish + kelp). Waste from one becomes input for another. Reduces environmental impact + provides multi-revenue streams. Bangs Island Mussels demonstrates IMTA in Maine.' },
      { q: 'How do I learn aquaculture if I\'m not in Maine?', a: 'Maine MAA + universities welcome out-of-state interest. UMaine Aquaculture Research Institute hosts international students. Online resources at FAO, NOAA, ASC. Maine aquaculture model has international relevance.' },
      { q: 'What\'s the role of women in Maine aquaculture?', a: 'Growing significantly. Briana Warner (Atlantic Sea Farms CEO) is industry leader; Sarah Redmond (Springtide); many women-owned farms emerging. Industry historically male-dominated but actively diversifying. Maine + national aquaculture associations supporting women + diverse leadership.' },
      { q: 'Do I need an MBA to run a successful aquaculture business?', a: 'No, but business skills are essential. Many successful farmers learn business through experience + mentors + CEI courses. Accounting + financial planning + marketing + management + people skills all matter. CEI + MAA provide business training resources.' },
      { q: 'How does ocean acidification affect Maine aquaculture?', a: 'Shellfish larvae are particularly sensitive to low pH. Mook Sea Farm pioneered buffer system that adjusts incoming water to optimal pH. Industry-wide adaptation needed as acidification continues. Climate-positive species (kelp) help buffer local pH while contributing carbon removal.' }
    ];

